whats an reit and what are the advantages disadvantages of it a reit is a real estate investment trust it gives you a way to invest in real estate mainly commercial without directly own any buldings shopping centers etc they are more liquid than direct ownership in real estate some reits invest in mortgages so you need to be able to differentiate between the differeing types of reits reits are yield vehicles which means they pay of their income out in the form of dividends the disadvantage is that you are tied to the real estate market which from time to time could experience liquidity credit issues like the mortgage market is experiencing Income trust Mortgage Dividend Insurance The Link REIT Securitization Cooperative Life insurance Taxation in the United States Debt Mortgage-backed security Government National Mortgage Association Corporation Corporate finance Concurrent estate Title insurance Security (finance) Gross domestic product Stock Capital accumulation Real estate bubble Tax Derivative (finance) United Kingdom corporation tax Monopoly (game) Interest Municipal bond Bank Supply-side economics Bretton Woods system Anarchism and capitalism Islamic banking Leasing Housing cooperative Futures contract Surplus value Deflation (economics) Real estate developer Property tax Flat tax Personal finance Annuity Microcredit Primerica Financial Services Trust (Law) USA Individual Retirement Account Warren Buffett Capitalism Lloyd's of London Land trust Yield curve Cost of capital Reaganomics Wealth condensation Personal rapid transit Donald Trump Productive and unproductive labour Wells Fargo Real property Allodial title Speculation Business Trust (Law) non-USA Eugene Fama Real estate broker Surveying Toronto-Dominion Bank PE ratio Nuclear power Intellectual property Microeconomics British residential property market Savings and loan association Personal property Investment bank Dividend imputation Financial markets History of the United States (1918-1945) Canadian Im